eligions from a wide range of backgrounds and vantage points, and draws from traditions as diverse as Indo-European mythology, ancient Greek religion, Judaism, Buddhism, Ndembu ritual, and the spectrum of religions practiced in America. The contributors take seriously the postmodern critique, explain its impact on their work, uphold or reject various premises, and in several cases demonstrate new comparative approaches. Together, the essays represent a state-of-the-art assessment of current issues in the comparative study of religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPostmodernism. 0aReligions. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aacademic.  abelief.  abuddhism.  acase study.  acolonial.  acolonialism.  acomparative religion.  adiscourse.  adiversity.  aessay anthology.  aessay collection.  afaith.  afolk tales.  afolklore.  agreek religion.  agreek.  aindo european.  ajudaism.  amethodology.  amythology.  andembu.  apostmodern.  areligion.  areligious studies.  aritual.  aritualistic.  ascholarly.  atradition.  atraditional.1 aDoinger, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEck, Diana L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckel, Malcom David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerman, Jonathan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoldrege, Barbara A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaden, William E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatton, Kimberley C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatton, Kimberley C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPatton, Laurie L., econtributor.4ctb